00:08:20.620 --> 00:08:24.699
So give us a little overview of how you think
your approach to problems differ

00:08:24.699 --> 00:08:28.379
than the average physicians approach
to health problems.

00:08:28.453 --> 00:08:29.779
Right, Bret.

00:08:29.779 --> 00:08:33.460
Well, essentially we use a lot of tools,
systematic tools.

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:35.340
So there is the Pareto principle,

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:38.860
which is a rack and stack of the most
important factors based on the evidence

00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:41.220
and that's really important.

00:08:41.220 --> 00:08:45.419
Those comparative analysis,
a tool called Kepner Tragoe,

00:08:45.419 --> 00:08:50.539
where you prosecute all of the distinctions
between what the problem is and is not

00:08:50.539 --> 00:08:53.059
and then you record the inferences.

00:08:53.059 --> 00:08:55.500
So it's kind of like
a little epidemiological.

00:08:55.500 --> 00:08:58.383
It's looking at all the differences
and what might cause them

00:08:58.384 --> 00:09:02.139
and that can become a very long list.

00:09:02.139 --> 00:09:06.419
And then there's hypothesis for
against charts,

00:09:06.419 --> 00:09:10.299
where you look at many hypothesis
for a single problem.

00:09:10.299 --> 00:09:13.100
And we split up many, many hypothesis

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:16.419
and they are constantly judged
against each other

00:09:16.419 --> 00:09:20.139
based on the evidence
for each individual one and against.

00:09:20.139 --> 00:09:23.299
And there's never any clarity early
in a complex problem,

00:09:23.299 --> 00:09:25.299
especially a multifactor.

00:09:25.299 --> 00:09:28.585
So you have many, many hypotheses
and they are pitched against each other.

00:09:28.586 --> 00:09:31.220
And that's
an enormously important discipline,

00:09:31.220 --> 00:09:33.740
which doesn't really happen in medicine.

00:09:33.740 --> 00:09:37.379
Usually a hypothesis gains ground,
becomes established,

00:09:37.379 --> 00:09:41.860
the orthodoxy get behind it
and it kind of transcends into dogma.

00:09:41.860 --> 00:09:44.139
So there's a huge difference.

00:09:44.139 --> 00:09:49.740
And then statistical inference and
design of experiments to test hypotheses

00:09:49.740 --> 00:09:52.019
is an automatic part of our life.

00:09:52.019 --> 00:09:58.419
An autopsy, so intense autopsy
with electron microscopes and other tools

00:09:58.419 --> 00:10:02.340
to dig in and scrutinize the problem
at a physical level.

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:04.974
And again you don't have
so much of that medicine.

00:10:05.278 --> 00:10:07.419
When I hear you go
through this checklist

00:10:07.419 --> 00:10:10.820
and then I think in my mind
how we write guidelines in medicine

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:13.019
and they're so polar opposite.

00:10:13.019 --> 00:10:15.860
I mean the guidelines are...
you get a group of people together

00:10:15.860 --> 00:10:18.940
that do a sort of a cursory evaluation
of the evidence,

00:10:18.940 --> 00:10:21.379
they come up
with their best case scenario

00:10:21.379 --> 00:10:23.460
and their opinions
of what the guidelines should be.

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:25.940
That is a far cry
from what you just described.

00:10:26.028 --> 00:10:29.299
And one crucial thing I'll just add,
there are many more tools,

00:10:29.299 --> 00:10:32.779
but also the experience
of decades of using these tools...

00:10:32.779 --> 00:10:38.059
you less and less make mistakes or jump
to conclusions through sheer experience.

00:10:38.059 --> 00:10:41.179
But a crucial one is to always look
for black swans,

00:10:41.179 --> 00:10:45.202
for contradictory evidence
against your hypothesis.

00:10:45.203 --> 00:10:50.500
So that's an enormous part of the time
to resolution and success in engineering

00:10:50.500 --> 00:10:54.539
is you look for negative data
that conflicts with your hypothesis

00:10:54.539 --> 00:10:57.779
and you rapidly kill incorrect hypotheses

00:10:57.779 --> 00:11:01.899
or you rewrite them
to accommodate the conflicting data.

00:11:01.899 --> 00:11:04.139
And that's just so central

00:11:04.139 --> 00:11:09.340
but I must say in nutritional medicine
that's the most extraordinary difference.

00:11:09.340 --> 00:11:13.460
Confirmatory data is always looked for

00:11:13.460 --> 00:11:17.179
to build up more and more evidence
to support a hypothesis,

00:11:17.179 --> 00:11:21.580
whereas one or two conflicting pieces
of data could reset the whole team

00:11:21.580 --> 00:11:25.019
and get you back on the correct path
doesn't happen.

00:11:25.118 --> 00:11:32.620
So we do have criteria in medicine
that prove or disprove hypotheses.

00:11:32.620 --> 00:11:37.820
And that's the Bradford Hill criteria,
but we've set the bar so low

00:11:37.820 --> 00:11:41.860
that we don't look at it
like a scientist or an engineer looks at it.

00:11:41.957 --> 00:11:46.100
Right and I wonder how many doctors
are even aware of the Bradford Hill criteria.

00:11:46.100 --> 00:11:49.419
And when you're interpreting
an observational study

00:11:49.419 --> 00:11:54.299
that shows a relative risk of 1.18
and that makes it as causative,

00:11:54.299 --> 00:11:57.412
which, you know, that doesn't even scratch
the Bradford Hill criteria,

00:11:57.413 --> 00:12:03.179
I think it's just an underused tool for sure.

00:12:03.261 --> 00:12:07.059
And actually another example
of Bradford Hill that just springs to mind,

00:12:07.059 --> 00:12:10.340
there has to be directionality
of dose-response.

00:12:10.340 --> 00:12:17.299
So cause X supposedly driving Y,
as X increases, why should increase?

00:12:17.299 --> 00:12:21.019
But we have many examples including
cholesterol and other things,

00:12:21.019 --> 00:12:24.299
whether is not a dose-response.

00:12:24.299 --> 00:12:27.700
Yes so Bradford Hill is excellent actually
in principle,

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:31.319
but it's utilization is almost zero
from what I've seen.

