00:15:44.353 --> 00:15:46.700
It's really important to clarify

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:51.740
and anyone that infers from the word
warranty it's zero is mistaking obviously.

00:15:51.740 --> 00:15:54.340
And the warranty I think
there were two papers

00:15:54.340 --> 00:15:57.659
were warranty was used
in the title of the publication

00:15:57.659 --> 00:16:00.059
and it probably is unfortunate.

00:16:00.059 --> 00:16:03.659
So one of the largest study showed
just from memory

00:16:03.659 --> 00:16:10.539
that zero scoring middle-age people I think
12 years later at 99.6% were still alive.

00:16:10.539 --> 00:16:16.019
And high-scoring people 75.6
were still alive.

00:16:16.019 --> 00:16:19.539
Now that's an enormous difference
in mortality.

00:16:19.539 --> 00:16:22.259
So although enormous, there's no zero,

00:16:22.259 --> 00:16:25.820
and I think Jeff you probably agree
that if you're zero calcium,

00:16:25.820 --> 00:16:27.899
there are exceptions.

00:16:27.899 --> 00:16:32.500
On one end there are people with zero who
have rapid progression of atherosclerosis

00:16:32.500 --> 00:16:36.100
and a soft plaque does rupture

00:16:36.100 --> 00:16:39.860
before there's significant calcification
to show up in the scan.

00:16:39.860 --> 00:16:43.860
I mean later you could look
and probably find diffuse calcification,

00:16:43.860 --> 00:16:45.940
but not enough to register.

00:16:45.940 --> 00:16:50.980
Interestingly on the other end of the scale
there's a small maybe 1% of people

00:16:50.980 --> 00:16:54.860
who have huge calcification
and who don't seem to have events

00:16:54.860 --> 00:16:59.179
and they appear to be the people
where the protective effect of calcification,

00:16:59.179 --> 00:17:02.980
which is to protect the arteries
when they're inflamed,

00:17:02.980 --> 00:17:06.380
is so advanced and rapidly progressing

00:17:06.380 --> 00:17:11.220
that they actually end up with massive
calcification but relatively stable arteries,

00:17:11.220 --> 00:17:13.740
they almost have a full metal jacket.

00:17:13.740 --> 00:17:17.195
So I think those two corner cases
around 1% at each end

00:17:17.196 --> 00:17:22.660
illustrate the protective nature of calcium,
it's a fantastic evolutionary process,

00:17:22.660 --> 00:17:26.619
it's actually bone matrix,
it's identical to bone matrix formation,

00:17:26.619 --> 00:17:31.740
but of course people rapidly progressing
may have their event

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:34.299
before the calcification establishes.

00:17:34.299 --> 00:17:38.180
So around 1% events
in the following 10 years

00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:45.059
for zero versus in your recent paper, Jeff,
around 37% for high scores close to 1,000.

00:17:45.059 --> 00:17:49.099
People just need to see
it's not 100% perfect.

00:17:49.209 --> 00:17:53.900
And that's a great point to bring up though
because I think we can fall into a trap

00:17:53.900 --> 00:17:58.380
of being sort of overly reassured
with a score of zero.

00:17:58.380 --> 00:18:01.859
It's not, "Your score is zero, see you later,
you don't have to worry about anything."

00:18:01.859 --> 00:18:05.140
It's, "Your score is zero,
but now you're on our radar screen

00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:07.572
to follow again to make sure
there's no progression."

00:18:07.681 --> 00:18:14.660
So one other point is criticism of the test
is that it doesn't visualize soft plaque.

00:18:14.660 --> 00:18:21.740
And when you look at the data first of all,
so when your score goes from zero to 1,000,

00:18:21.740 --> 00:18:25.940
this is independent of whether you see
soft plaque or not.

00:18:25.940 --> 00:18:31.940
If you have a zero score you still have
a small chance of having an event.

00:18:31.940 --> 00:18:35.140
Now the question is
if you can visualize soft plaque,

00:18:35.140 --> 00:18:38.619
would that change
your ability to predict risk

00:18:38.619 --> 00:18:42.180
for these people that have
a low calcium score?

00:18:42.180 --> 00:18:47.420
So you can do a CTMR,
you could do a CT angiogram

00:18:47.420 --> 00:18:50.539
and then you get to see the soft plaque.

00:18:50.539 --> 00:18:55.859
But in our experience it doesn't change
the data

00:18:55.859 --> 00:18:58.731
looking at a CT calcium by itself.

00:18:58.838 --> 00:19:01.740
So Jeff, what do you think about
the carotid intima media thickness

00:19:01.740 --> 00:19:03.700
as a surrogate for that?

00:19:03.700 --> 00:19:05.740
Obviously again we're not talking

00:19:05.740 --> 00:19:08.339
about the specific site
we're concerned about

00:19:08.339 --> 00:19:10.619
and we're not even talking
about plaque so much.

00:19:10.619 --> 00:19:13.059
It's just the thickness of the intima
of the carotid artery,

00:19:13.059 --> 00:19:16.819
but something you can measure quickly
without radiation

00:19:16.819 --> 00:19:19.875
that might be a decent surrogate marker
for the soft plaque as well.

00:19:19.961 --> 00:19:23.740
Yeah, so again you describe
that nice...

00:19:23.740 --> 00:19:28.819
Well, the intima is just the lining
of the wall of the artery

00:19:28.819 --> 00:19:33.220
and so I don't know
who created the technology,

00:19:33.220 --> 00:19:37.539
but what he tried to do
was to age the blood vessel

00:19:37.539 --> 00:19:41.259
based on the thickness of the intima.

00:19:41.259 --> 00:19:49.180
And on literature review it really does not
correlate with events and mortality.

00:19:49.180 --> 00:19:54.660
So it's interesting, in our office
we actually do the CIMT,

00:19:54.660 --> 00:19:57.779
because it comes along
with a limited Doppler.

00:19:57.779 --> 00:20:01.460
So the limited Doppler, we're actually
looking for plaque buildup

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:03.740
within the lumen itself.

00:20:03.740 --> 00:20:07.859
And that perhaps is a surrogate test
for say a coronary calcium score.

00:20:07.859 --> 00:20:11.380
It's not quantifiable
quite like a coronary calcium score.

00:20:11.380 --> 00:20:15.099
The idea is if you could image
all the blood vessels in the body

00:20:15.099 --> 00:20:17.900
and look at the plaque burden,

00:20:17.900 --> 00:20:21.220
that would give you a great idea
about overall risk.

00:20:21.220 --> 00:20:23.420
But we do like the calcium score,

00:20:23.420 --> 00:20:26.259
because it's looking
at those tiny little coronary arteries

00:20:26.259 --> 00:20:29.940
that, you know, you are at risk
for heart attack and stroke.

00:20:29.940 --> 00:20:33.259
So CIMT doesn't really correlate.

00:20:33.355 --> 00:20:37.819
I'd like to see the rate of change study
sort of like with the coronary calcium score

00:20:37.819 --> 00:20:43.500
that has a fast change or slow change,
same for CIMT, and correlate that.

00:20:43.500 --> 00:20:46.923
I don't know if the rate of change studies
have been done quite as well.

00:20:47.049 --> 00:20:49.099
No not really.

00:20:49.099 --> 00:20:55.579
In fact there's not much really linking CIMT
impressively to future risk prediction.

00:20:55.579 --> 00:20:58.660
I mean it's a useful tool
to quantify and track,

00:20:58.660 --> 00:21:01.579
but it's just very weak
compared to calcium.

00:21:01.579 --> 00:21:04.660
Because as you say it's surrogate
in different vessel,

00:21:04.660 --> 00:21:07.980
there is operator variation, quite large,

00:21:07.980 --> 00:21:12.019
they have to pick the region, you know,
with to mouse clicks.

00:21:12.019 --> 00:21:16.980
And you can't have people who have
quite a large intimal thickening,

00:21:16.980 --> 00:21:21.779
but really have very stable arteries
with no real vulnerable plaque

00:21:21.779 --> 00:21:24.299
and vice versa.

00:21:24.299 --> 00:21:26.779
It's just the calcium is vastly better.

00:21:26.779 --> 00:21:29.380
You did mention an interesting point,
the radiation,

00:21:29.380 --> 00:21:32.660
and I researched that myself
out of interest because I often hear this,

00:21:32.660 --> 00:21:35.819
but machines nowadays are around 1 mSv,

00:21:35.819 --> 00:21:38.619
which is around the same
as a bilateral mammogram.

00:21:38.619 --> 00:21:41.380
And if you look back at research
in the past decades,

00:21:41.380 --> 00:21:45.779
Chernobyl and even Hiroshima
and the nuclear accident in Brazil,

00:21:45.779 --> 00:21:49.220
the biggest civilian nuclear accident,

00:21:49.220 --> 00:21:54.339
they tracked the people who had
much, much higher exposures than this.

00:21:54.339 --> 00:21:56.259
I mean much higher.

00:21:56.259 --> 00:22:00.140
And generally over decades
no signal between them and controls.

00:22:00.140 --> 00:22:04.299
So I think the expert Douglas Boyd
who invented the calcium scanner,

00:22:04.299 --> 00:22:06.420
I interviewed him the other day,

00:22:06.420 --> 00:22:10.660
he said that that risk is maybe one in 10,000
of some possibility,

00:22:10.660 --> 00:22:15.259
it's theoretical for 41 mSv, it's tiny

00:22:15.259 --> 00:22:20.180
and it really is a distraction
from the topic of how powerful the scan is.

00:22:20.527 --> 00:22:24.619
Yeah, that's a great point about
how we interpret the risk of radiation,

00:22:24.619 --> 00:22:29.740
because in medicine there's this concept
of ALARA, as low as reasonably acceptable,

00:22:29.740 --> 00:22:35.059
and it almost teaches us
to think of it as a way...

00:22:35.059 --> 00:22:38.180
it doesn't matters
how high the radiation exposure is.

00:22:38.180 --> 00:22:41.900
What matters is how much is the test
going to contribute to the care.

00:22:41.900 --> 00:22:45.500
And is it worth it
for any amount of radiation exposure?

00:22:45.500 --> 00:22:51.120
Certainly a one-time calcium score
or following every five years or so.

00:22:51.121 --> 00:22:54.900
Where I get a little concerned is if someone
wants to follow a calcium score

00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:57.099
every six months or everyone year,

00:22:57.099 --> 00:23:01.420
because we don't have data to say that
short-term of a progression on happens

00:23:01.420 --> 00:23:04.980
or what it means,
but more of the longer term following.

00:23:04.980 --> 00:23:07.019
Would you agree with that statement?

00:23:07.107 --> 00:23:08.299
Yeah.

00:23:08.299 --> 00:23:12.220
So interestingly I've been working
with my hospital next-door,

00:23:12.220 --> 00:23:18.019
that they've had a 64 slice GE machine
for quite some time, GE Optima,

00:23:18.019 --> 00:23:23.220
and last year they purchased
the cardiac package.

00:23:23.220 --> 00:23:25.420
And I've been bugging them right next door,

00:23:25.420 --> 00:23:28.619
I said, "Hey, we got to get this thing set up
for calcium scans."

00:23:28.619 --> 00:23:32.420
And I've learned a lot because I've sat
in there with their radiologist,

00:23:32.420 --> 00:23:35.380
the radiology technician over lunch,

00:23:35.380 --> 00:23:38.220
we just sit down and just... 
fascinating stuff.

00:23:38.220 --> 00:23:44.299
And first of all there's much less
user input error

00:23:44.299 --> 00:23:46.460
when you do this calcium score.

00:23:46.460 --> 00:23:48.619
You know, they calibrate the machine

00:23:48.619 --> 00:23:52.220
and the machine does the calculation
to measure the calcium.

00:23:52.220 --> 00:23:56.380
And I actually have been looking
at the studies.

00:23:56.380 --> 00:24:03.099
So the radiating dosage,
so the effective radiation dosage...

00:24:03.099 --> 00:24:10.980
So the device puts out a certain amount
of radiation, so it'll measure in DLP units,

00:24:10.980 --> 00:24:14.900
and I think our machine is about 165 DLP.

00:24:14.900 --> 00:24:17.819
So that is what the machine puts out

00:24:17.819 --> 00:24:22.859
and then you have to do a fudge factor
calculation for the effective dosage.

00:24:22.859 --> 00:24:27.059
So there's a chest factor.

00:24:27.059 --> 00:24:31.779
And when we do the calculation,
our calcium score is...

00:24:31.779 --> 00:24:34.953
the millisieverts is about 1.2.

00:24:34.954 --> 00:24:38.460
And so you know I'm watching that
really carefully

00:24:38.460 --> 00:24:43.299
and there's things that the technicians
can do so they can make a smaller window

00:24:43.299 --> 00:24:48.500
and the idea 
is that really is a small dosage.

00:24:48.500 --> 00:24:54.660
And if you have a zero score you could
probably say that you don't need any more,

00:24:54.660 --> 00:24:59.700
but it is okay to track...
you can track every 3 to 5 years,

00:24:59.700 --> 00:25:01.980
maybe sooner if people are concerned.

00:25:02.079 --> 00:25:05.539
Yeah, especially if someone's changed
their lifestyle significantly

00:25:05.539 --> 00:25:08.019
and you want to see what impact that has.

00:25:08.019 --> 00:25:11.500
So yeah, I think that's a pretty good
summary of calcium score.

00:25:11.500 --> 00:25:16.875
Let's transition to a second about...
transition to weight loss.

00:25:16.876 --> 00:25:20.259
Jeff, you talked about weight loss
in your talk today

00:25:20.259 --> 00:25:25.140
and what is so interesting
is a lot of people come to a low-carb diet

00:25:25.140 --> 00:25:26.980
for the purpose of weight loss.

00:25:26.980 --> 00:25:29.739
But would you say weight loss
is the most important metric to follow?

00:25:29.841 --> 00:25:31.900
No, not at all.

00:25:31.900 --> 00:25:35.140
So again as I mentioned earlier,

00:25:35.140 --> 00:25:39.940
my understanding of cardiovascular disease
led me to the metabolic syndrome.

00:25:39.940 --> 00:25:43.700
And so I think why we're here
as engineers and doctors

00:25:43.700 --> 00:25:48.980
is we're trying to understand how do treat
and prevent chronic disease.

00:25:48.980 --> 00:25:54.932
And weight loss is just kind
of a consequence of doing all this.

00:25:55.033 --> 00:25:59.140
And so, Ivor, when we talk about
the mechanisms of weight loss

00:25:59.140 --> 00:26:02.420
or the mechanisms
of improving metabolic health,

00:26:02.420 --> 00:26:04.980
there's the debate
of the calories in calories out

00:26:04.980 --> 00:26:07.579
versus the carbohydrate insulin model

00:26:07.579 --> 00:26:11.998
or some combination thereof
when you factor in psychological factors...

00:26:11.999 --> 00:26:17.205
How do you break down and say what is
the reason why a low-carb diet works?

00:26:18.114 --> 00:26:21.099
Yeah, that's 
the million-dollar question.

00:26:21.099 --> 00:26:23.099
So I will take a shot at it.

00:26:23.099 --> 00:26:27.380
I think that calories... there is a place
for calories, there's no question.

00:26:27.380 --> 00:26:33.460
It's not like the CI-CO,
that is simply eat less, move more,

00:26:33.460 --> 00:26:36.259
because the body is
far more complex than that,

00:26:36.259 --> 00:26:39.220
with myriad hormonal control
feedback loops.

00:26:39.220 --> 00:26:42.420
So I think the primary benefit
of a low-carb diet

00:26:42.420 --> 00:26:45.460
actually is appetite control
and management.

00:26:45.460 --> 00:26:47.874
It's a really big factor.

00:26:47.875 --> 00:26:52.420
So when I went on a low-carb diet,
and I'm not speaking N=1,

00:26:52.420 --> 00:26:55.380
but it's seen in studies
and all over the place,

00:26:55.380 --> 00:27:01.460
ad lib. low-carb diets have beaten
calorie controlled low-fat diets.

00:27:01.460 --> 00:27:06.420
And we see again and again that when you
switch over from a glucose based metabolism

00:27:06.420 --> 00:27:08.660
to a more fat burning metabolism,

00:27:08.660 --> 00:27:10.660
appetite comes under your control.

00:27:10.660 --> 00:27:12.579
In my case it was striking.

00:27:12.579 --> 00:27:14.819
I was actually shocked within weeks

00:27:14.819 --> 00:27:19.424
of how I could blithely not have to eat
when I didn't want to.

00:27:19.425 --> 00:27:22.142
So I think that's one of the big factors.

00:27:22.143 --> 00:27:26.019
Now when your insulin is high
and you are hyperinsulinemic,

00:27:26.019 --> 00:27:29.660
like probably the majority
of American adults today,

00:27:29.660 --> 00:27:33.059
that will tend towards trapping fat

00:27:33.059 --> 00:27:38.339
and tend against the burning
of your body fat, so that is another factor.

00:27:38.339 --> 00:27:41.900
But I would say appetite control
is the central linchpin

00:27:41.900 --> 00:27:45.940
with the metabolic advantage
that's being discussed

00:27:45.940 --> 00:27:50.539
and the lowering of insulin
being another strong element,

00:27:50.539 --> 00:27:53.417
but it's not fully quantified,
I think that's fair to say.

00:27:53.418 --> 00:27:55.819
What would you say, Jeff?

00:27:55.915 --> 00:28:00.380
Yes, so there's a lot of factor to consider
that it's not necessarily all insulin.

00:28:00.380 --> 00:28:08.099
There's many hormones and signals
such as leptin, the gut incretins,

00:28:08.099 --> 00:28:13.579
we have to all consider that when
we are thinking about regulating appetite,

00:28:13.579 --> 00:28:20.019
but of course insulin is probably
the master hormone involved.

00:28:20.019 --> 00:28:27.859
And when you consider that perhaps
two thirds of the US population adults

00:28:27.859 --> 00:28:31.539
over age 45 are currently diabetic
and prediabetic

00:28:31.539 --> 00:28:37.700
that when you treat them
with carbohydrate restriction,

00:28:37.700 --> 00:28:39.740
you're going to have most success.

00:28:39.957 --> 00:28:42.819
And I think that's a very good answer

00:28:42.819 --> 00:28:46.579
because we like to simplify things
and almost to a fault,

00:28:46.579 --> 00:28:49.019
because we want to know,
"Is it the calories in, calories out?

00:28:49.019 --> 00:28:50.940
Is it the carbohydrate insulin?"

00:28:50.940 --> 00:28:53.420
And the truth is
it's far more complex than that.

00:28:53.420 --> 00:28:57.099
That's basically how I would summarize
your answer, so I thank you for that.

00:28:57.099 --> 00:28:59.259
The next question though Jeff is

00:28:59.259 --> 00:29:01.859
I'm sure you see these patients
all the time in your office

00:29:01.859 --> 00:29:04.460
that they come in with a stall.

00:29:04.460 --> 00:29:06.660
And you can define the stall
on different ways,

00:29:06.660 --> 00:29:09.108
but basically whatever metric
they are following,

00:29:09.109 --> 00:29:12.460
whether it's their weight loss,
whether it's their insulin sensitivity,

00:29:12.460 --> 00:29:15.900
it just plateaus and they get frustrated.

00:29:15.900 --> 00:29:20.660
What kind of advice can you give to people
about your general approach?

00:29:20.660 --> 00:29:23.140
When you see a stall
what do you think about...

00:29:23.140 --> 00:29:27.299
what are your sort of go to top two
or three things to ask them to do?

00:29:27.400 --> 00:29:32.339
Right, so if you're insulin resistant
you just respond rapidly,

00:29:32.339 --> 00:29:37.500
your appetite is controlled,
you correct insulin resistance

00:29:37.500 --> 00:29:42.259
and the fat that is trapped in a damper
behind insulin...

00:29:42.259 --> 00:29:47.980
it opens these insulin floodgates
and energy just pours out from fat tissue.

00:29:47.980 --> 00:29:50.700
But what often happens

00:29:50.700 --> 00:29:55.299
and I mean I'm just thinking
of a patient I saw last week...

00:29:55.299 --> 00:29:58.460
they never lost weight
from the beginning

00:29:58.460 --> 00:30:01.259
even though they were
markedly insulin resistant

00:30:01.259 --> 00:30:04.180
when we measured all the parameters.

00:30:06.299 --> 00:30:10.539
This particular person was told by a trainer,

00:30:10.539 --> 00:30:15.099
"You have to eat 180 g of fat a day.

00:30:15.099 --> 00:30:18.140
No matter if you're hungry or not hungry."

00:30:18.140 --> 00:30:22.579
And she was heeding the advice
and pumping in the fat.

00:30:22.579 --> 00:30:24.740
And nothing happened.

00:30:24.740 --> 00:30:27.259
I mean that's just an extreme example,

00:30:27.259 --> 00:30:33.460
but the point is that what you are eating
at the beginning

00:30:33.460 --> 00:30:37.019
is not going to be the same
when you hit this plateau.

00:30:37.019 --> 00:30:39.940
And so guess what?

00:30:39.940 --> 00:30:42.779
Controlling appetite
becomes most important.

00:30:42.779 --> 00:30:47.380
This is what I think about, the quantity
of food that you consume,

00:30:47.380 --> 00:30:51.779
the calories the activity
and then it trickles downhill.

00:30:51.779 --> 00:30:56.019
But we have to make people understand

00:30:56.019 --> 00:31:02.097
that the quantity of food is really important
once you become more insulin sensitive.

00:31:02.441 --> 00:31:03.859
Yeah, very good point.

00:31:03.859 --> 00:31:06.339
And now to tag onto that a little bit more,

00:31:06.339 --> 00:31:09.220
to go a little bit deeper
into the specifics of the diet...

00:31:09.220 --> 00:31:11.500
Ivor, this one's for you
as a good Irishman...

00:31:11.500 --> 00:31:15.539
How does alcohol fit into the low-carb diet
and the low-carb lifestyle?

00:31:15.651 --> 00:31:18.140
Rather well.

00:31:18.140 --> 00:31:24.299
No, actually alcohol, I think a glass or two
of red wine a day is fine.

00:31:24.299 --> 00:31:27.539
You know, the beers are generally carby.

00:31:27.539 --> 00:31:30.299
I've heard beer described as liquid bread,
which is a pretty good.

00:31:30.370 --> 00:31:31.900
A good description.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:34.940
Yeah so I think generally alcohol...

00:31:34.940 --> 00:31:38.619
interestingly there are studies done
in the 60s on humans

00:31:38.619 --> 00:31:44.539
and calorie controlled, calorie for calorie
alcohol replacing carbohydrate

00:31:44.539 --> 00:31:47.700
led to a slight drop in weight.

